## Slide 6 - Is MMA-TP just a fancy prompt?

**Slide message:** No. A large prompt is a block of instructions. MMA-TP is a structured interaction scaffold with phases, gates, transitions, and constraints that continue to shape the session.

This slide is the conceptual center of the presentation.

A large prompt can guide early behavior, but it is still mostly natural language instruction. It may describe what the tutor should do, but it does not necessarily create a reusable state structure that the tutor must continually reference.

MMA-TP changes the interaction pattern by adding:

- named states;
- gate conditions;
- pass/fail transitions;
- allowed and prohibited responses;
- diagnostic tags;
- remediation rules;
- phase-specific response limits.

As the tutor moves through the lesson, it repeatedly references the structure. Those repeated references become additional context that reinforces the protocol. The model is not only influenced by the original prompt; it is also influenced by its own protocol-consistent behavior across the session.

Professional version of the core idea:

> A prompt tells the model what kind of tutor to be. MMA-TP gives the tutor a persistent interaction map and requires it to keep locating the learner inside that map.

This is why MMA-TP can sometimes preserve behavioral structure even after the original prompt is no longer the dominant part of the visible conversation. The session itself becomes saturated with state labels, gate decisions, constraint language, and structured transitions.

Important claim boundary:

- This is not a mathematical guarantee.
- This is not formal runtime enforcement.
- It is structured contextual conditioning.

Recommended speaker framing:

> The difference is that MMA-TP does not rely on a single instruction staying powerful forever. It creates a repeated behavioral loop. Every time the tutor checks a gate, refuses a shortcut, gives a phase-specific hint, or explains the next step, it reintroduces the protocol back into the context.


