## Slide 8 - Empirical results

**Slide message:** MMA-TP was evaluated against prompt-only tutoring baselines across 50 sessions.

The published paper reports an evaluation across five instructional tasks:

- Python for-loops;
- Java if/else conditionals;
- web application fundamentals;
- C++ functions;
- operating systems review.

For each task, five MMA-TP sessions and five prompt-only baseline sessions were conducted, producing 50 total sessions: 25 MMA-TP and 25 prompt-only.

The evaluation focused on structural behavior, not student learning outcomes. The measured behavioral categories included:

- premature solution disclosure;
- phase order violations;
- structural collapse.

Published results summarized:

- MMA-TP showed no premature solution disclosure across 25 evaluated sessions.
- Prompt-only baselines disclosed solutions prematurely in 19 of 25 sessions.
- MMA-TP preserved declared phase order and guardrail enforcement in 23 of 25 sessions.
- No MMA-TP session exhibited full structural collapse.

The two observed MMA-TP deviations should be framed carefully. They did not represent total protocol failure. One involved pre-existing platform/account-level conditioning, and another required sustained attempts to override the protocol. In both cases, the overall checkpoint structure remained present.

Recommended speaker framing:

> These results do not prove that MMA-TP makes LLM tutoring perfect. They show that, in the tested sessions, structured prompt/specification pairing preserved tutoring structure more reliably than prompt-only instruction.


